First, let's simplify the numerator using the sum-to-product identity for cosine:

$$\frac{1}{2}(\cos(65^\circ) + \cos(25^\circ)) = \frac{1}{2}\left[\cos(90^\circ - 30^\circ) + \cos(105^\circ)\right]$$

Using the sum-to-product identity for cosine:

\begin{align*}
\tan \theta &= \frac{\cos 5^\circ \cos 20^\circ + \cos 35^\circ \cos 50^\circ - \sin 5^\circ \sin 20^\circ - \sin 35^\circ \sin 50^\circ}{\sin 5^\circ \cos 20^\circ - \sin 35^\circ \cos 50^\circ + \cos 5^\circ \sin 20^\circ - \cos 35^\circ \sin 50^\circ} \\
